Extracting results:

limmaRes <- list() 
for(coefx in colnames(coef(limmaFit))){ 
  print(coefx)
  # topTable returns the statistics of our genes. We then store the result of each coefficient in a list.
  # The rownames (ENSEMBL Gene IDs) are stored in the column with the name "ensg"
  limmaRes[[coefx]] <- topTable(limmaFit, coef=coefx,number = Inf) |>
    rownames_to_column("ensg")
}
## [1] "(Intercept)"
## [1] "stimulusIFNa"
## [1] "stimulusIFNg"
## [1] "stimulusIL3"
## [1] "stimulusIL6"
## [1] "stimulusTGFb"
## [1] "stimulusTNF"
limmaRes <- bind_rows(limmaRes, .id = "coef") # bind_rows combines the results and stores the name of the coefficient in the column "coef"
limmaRes <- filter(limmaRes, coef != "(Intercept)") # then we keep all results except for the intercept

Enrichment analysis
Enrichment analysis for each coefficient 
fisher_list <- list()
for(coefx in unique(limmaResSig$coef)){
  
  # What is coefx now?
  message(coefx)
  
  # Extract genes of interests (GOI) for a given coefficient (see yesterday's example)
  goi <- limmaResSig %>% filter(coef == coefx) %>% pull(ensg)
  goi <- gmap[goi, ]$external_gene_name |> unique()
  print(goi)
  
  universe <- unique(gmap$external_gene_name)
  universe <- unique(universe[!is.na(universe) & universe != ""])
  MSigDB <- readRDS("MSigDB.rds")
  fisher_tbl <- map_df(names(MSigDB), function(pw) {
    pw_genes <- MSigDB[[pw]]
    sig_genes <- goi
    overlap <- intersect(sig_genes, pw_genes)
    a <- length(overlap)
    b <- length(sig_genes) - a
    c <- length(pw_genes) - a
    d <- length(universe) - (a+b+c)
    
    ft <- fisher.test(matrix(c(a,b,c,d),2), alternative = "greater")
    
    tibble(
      pathway = pw,
      pvalue = ft$p.value,
      odds_ratio = as.numeric(ft$estimate),
      DE_in_pathway = a,
      overlapping_genes = paste(overlap, collapse = ",")
    )
  })
  fisher_tbl <- fisher_tbl |> mutate(p_adj = p.adjust(pvalue, "BH"))
  print(head(fisher_tbl))
  
  # Store results in the list
  fisher_list[[coefx]] <- fisher_tbl
}

3.7) Generate an enrichment analysis plot (top 10 pathways based on most significant(lowest p-value) per coef.) 
top_10 <- fisher_tbl %>%
  mutate(
    coef = sub("^stimulus", "", coef),   # removing the prefix "stimulus"
  ) %>%
  group_by(coef) %>%
  arrange(p_adj, .by_group = TRUE) %>%
  slice_head(n = 10) %>%
  ungroup()
ggplot(top_10, aes(
  x = coef,
  y = reorder(pathway, odds_ratio),
  size = -log10(p_adj),
  color = log2(odds_ratio)
)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_size_continuous(name = "-log10(p_adj)") +
  scale_color_gradient2(low = "white", high = "red", name = "log2(odds_ratio)") +
  labs(
    x = "Type of stimulus",
    y = "Pathway",
    title = "Top 10 Enriched Pathways per Coefficient"
  ) +
  theme(
    axis.text.y = element_text(size = 10),
    plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", hjust = 0.5)
  )

Extracting genes underlying the above enrichments 
goi.enr <- fisher_tbl |>
  filter(p_adj < 0.05 & odds_ratio > 5) |>
  pull("overlapping_genes") |>
  str_split(",") |> 
  unlist() |>
  unique()

limmaRes.filter <- limmaRes %>%
  mutate(
    coef = sub("^stimulus", "", coef),   # removing the prefix "stimulus"
    gene = gmap[ensg,]$external_gene_name # making "gene" column 
  ) %>%
  filter(gene %in% goi.enr)

Final Questions
3.9) Looking at the correlation heatmap and MDS plot - do you see strong effects and clear differences between groups?

The heatmap indicates high within-group correlation, as samples stimulated with the same cytokines tend to cluster together. IFNg, TGFb and IL3 shows clear separation from the other groups, indicating that these stimuli induce different pathways.

This is somewhat confirmed by the MDS Plot, with IFNg forming a separate cluster in relation to other cytokines, although clustering is seen less proeminently here.

Correlation heatmap:

Heatmap(corMT,
        row_names_gp = gpar(fontsize = 8),
        column_names_gp = gpar(fontsize = 8))

MDS plot:

data.frame(cmdscale(dist(2-corMT),eig=TRUE, k=2)$points) |>
  add_column(stimulus = metadata$stimulus) |>
  rownames_to_column("sample") |>
  mutate(sn = str_replace(sample, "^.+?_(\\d)$", "\\1")) |> # This shortens the sample names to just the number at the end
  ggplot(aes(x=X1,y=X2)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color=stimulus)) +
  geom_text(aes(label=sn)) +
  theme_bw()

3.10) Which treatment has the largest effects? How do you judge this? Which treatment effects most genes? Which treatment has the largest (positive or negative) log fold changes? Are those two consistent?

The treatment with the highest effects in gene expression is IFNa, as judging by the highest logFC values:

limmaRes %>%
  group_by(coef) %>%
  summarize(max_logFC = max(logFC),
            min_logFC = min(logFC)) %>%
  arrange(desc(abs(max_logFC)))
